    <field name="scopecontent_teim">Record Group IV, Series A, Subseries 1, subsubseries d, pertains to Eben Norton Horsford's professional life in the form of communication with entrepreneurs, medical inspectors, physicians, and a variety of high-ranking officials from the U.S. Army and Navy during the American Civil War. Subsubseries d features seventy-six letters (183 pages) that document Horsford's unsuccessful trial manufacture of a chemically-enhanced ration of grain and meat designed to provide nutrition to troops. These contents trace the progression of Horsford's recipe with word from Albion Parris Howe, Amos Beebe Eaton, Colonel John Cunningham Kelton, Dr. Ferdinand Vandeveer Hayden, General George Gordon Meade, General Marsena Rudolph Patrick, General Ulysses S. Grant, Lewis Henry Morgan, Lieutenant Colonel William B. Guernsey, Quartermaster General Montgomery Cunningham Meigs, Rear Admiral Charles Henry Davis, and Secretary of War, Edwin McMasters Stanton. In addition, this subsubseries includes a uniquely negative critique of Horsford's chemical creation from Union soldier "L.R. Williams," who served in the 5th Regiment, Kansas Volunteer Calvary. </field>
    <field name="scopecontent_teim">These materials are arranged alphabetically by the company name or surname of the individual in contact. </field>
    <field name="scopecontent_teim">Record titles reflect this arrangement by taking the form: 
[Surname, First Name]: [Location]. </field>
    <field name="scopecontent_teim">In the case that a set of correspondence includes multiple authors or the surname of the individual are unidentified, record titles reflect administrative categories, first names, initials, or nicknames, with possible surnames and locations provided in brackets. In the case that a record includes more than one date expression, the listing will begin with its earliest. If a record is physically undated, approximate ranges are provided. These records are noted "undated" and followed by a "circa" estimate determined by the range represented in the same subseries.</field>
